<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1082,1503]" pageId="11" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,333,1226,1251]" pageId="11" pageNumber="42">Comments.</emphasis>
This species was known only from the East Pamirs (
<collectingCountry box="[947,1061,1226,1250]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="11" pageNumber="42">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Sychevskaya" box="[1086,1364,1226,1250]" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" refString="Sychevskaya, V. I. (1970) Zonal distribution of coprophilous and necrophilous flies (Diptera) in Middle Asia. Entomologicheskoe Obozrenie, 49, 819 - 831. [In Russian, with English summary.] [English translation in Entomological Review (Washington), 49, 498 - 505.]" type="book chapter" year="1970">
Sychevskaya 
<number box="[1244,1304,1226,1250]" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" value="1970.0">1970</number>
: 
<number box="[1318,1364,1226,1250]" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" value="827.0">827</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Two adults were recorded by V. Sychevskaya from the subalpine zone, up to 
<quantity box="[964,1052,1262,1286]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" unit="m" value="4200.0">4200 m</quantity>
, on faeces and on a window. During fieldwork in the Altai Mountains of Siberia this species was collected by Anatoliy Barkalov next to an Altai Marmot burrow. This species is also included in the list of 
<taxonomicName box="[810,919,1334,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Muscidae</taxonomicName>
associated with Marmot burrows because the species that it most closely resembles morphologically, the European species 
<taxonomicName authority="Pokorny" authorityName="Pokorny" box="[1021,1349,1370,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Mydaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufinervis">
<emphasis box="[1021,1225,1371,1395]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="42">Mydaea rufinervis</emphasis>
(Pokorny)
</taxonomicName>
, is well known as a “Marmot Fly” (
<bibRefCitation author="Pont" box="[463,716,1406,1430]" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" refString="Pont, A. C. &amp; Ackland, D. M. (1995) Fanniidae, Muscidae and Anthomyiidae associated with burrows of the Alpine Marmot (Marmota marmota Linnaeus) in the Upper Oetz Valley (Tyrol, Austria) (Insecta, Diptera). Bericht des naturwissenschaftlich-medizinischen Vereins in Innsbruck, 82, 319 - 324." type="journal article" year="1995">
Pont &amp; Ackland 
<number box="[657,716,1406,1430]" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). These two species share a number of synapomorphies such as enlarged gena, small eyes, etc. In the Alps, 
<taxonomicName box="[628,772,1443,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Mydaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufinervis">
<emphasis box="[628,772,1443,1467]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="42">M. rufinervis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs commonly at the entrance to burrows, but also along the sides of nearby paths and in the grassy vegetation.
</paragraph>
